verum. The constr. is ‘tu poscis vilia, verum [poscis] dante minor,' ‘what you ask is worthless‚ but in asking it you humble yourself to the giver.' This (or ‘verum es ') is the reading of all MSS. of authority, in- cluding all the Bland. Horace sre- quently begins a clause or sentence with ‘ verum’ at the end of a line and after a stop: Sat. 1. 2. 923 Epp.1.1. So, 2. 2. 70, 106; A. P. 303.
